<div class="indented"><a id="comment-190724"></a>
<div class="comment comment-by-node-author clearfix">
  
    <h3 class="comment__title"><a href="/comment/190724#comment-190724" class="permalink" rel="bookmark">Libertarianism vs. overshoot</a></h3>
  
  <div class="submitted subtext">
    Submitted by <a href="/experts/michael-mills-phd">Michael Mills Ph.D.</a> on November 3, 2011 - 4:55pm  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-name-comment-body field-type-text-long field-label-hidden">
        <div class="field__item"><p>Politically, I generally share your libertarian sentiments.  </p>
<p>However, if we will all be paying a severe price due to others' actions (health care costs for smokers, diabetics, etc.), then those actions become our concern.   </p>
<p>Easter Islanders had an interest in preventing others from cutting down trees on their island -- but they apparently did not act on that mutual interest.  </p>
<p>So, imho, there are some situations in which limitation of individual liberties are justified (although I would prefer that not to be the case), in this case, preventing ecological overshoot.</p>
</div>
  </div>
      </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment-reply first"><a href="/comment/reply/78532/190724">Reply to Michael Mills Ph.D.</a></li>
